Duty/Obligation: a moral imperative that prescribes a certain action or behaviour. 
e.g., "You shall not lie"

Absolute Duty: A duty that admits no exceptions and cannot be outweighed by any other moral consideration.
e.g., if "You shall not lie" is an absolute duty, then in no circumstance you're allowed to lie.

Prima-Facie Duty: A duty that grounds a presumption in favor of the recommended action, but might be outweighed
and may have exceptions. 
e.g., "You shall not kill", but you can lie to save someone's life (the duty is outweighed by a stronger duty) and you can 
lie if you're role-playing (exception).

Reparative Duties: Duties to make up for your errors. 
e.g., "If you treat someone unjustly, apologize"

Contrary-to-Duty Obligation: Obligations that apply when a prior duty has been violated.
e.g., "Support your classmate who is being bullied", when, ideally, your classmate should not be bullied to begin with.  

Ranking of duties: An order over duties that instructs on their relative strengths. 
e.g., "You shall help people in severe danger" > "You shall not lie"

Values: Features of an action or a state that makes it morally desirable. Although they do not express an obligation directly, 
they do imply it indirectly, namely an obligation to promote and/or protect the value.
e.g., "Kindness is good". Several obligations follows from the value, e.g., "Show gratitude to the lady tha helped you carrying your heavy luggages".

Open-textured value: A value that does not entirely specify when it is relevant.
e.g., "Helping others is good", generally means that you ought to help others, but you don't have to help all the people all the
time. It's is up to you to implement this value in practice. 
